MxLTBBtlIRuLh8B%2FKLVQfVcDyApNKmoezXO81r7hc7MI%2FGtWJYbtGPf%2B7%2BobvGDKT7OnRzz37zP6im7Gf%2FSyk6rpf%2B1eD67dnVVFLsF1PaapFe9acDaBUBFPZT9swfIuDBvjHr%2FSbZuP8vcEktLA%3D%3D" id="w1_2_3_5_6"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#f2ccc0;strokeColor=#c96a4a;fontColor=#5a2410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1065" y="717" width="236" height="108" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Meat-eater problem&lt;br&gt;(saved humans eat animals)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+5+6+7]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;(Michael Dickens, Vasco Grilo)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + meat_eater_problem&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The meat-eater problem: a dollar of human global health also buys decades of that person&#x27;s meat consumption, and factory farming it causes suffering the animal circle now counts. Each present-human org is charged an additive penalty — farmed-animal life-years caused per human DALY, times the suffering per factory-farmed life-year, times the animal&#x27;s welfare range. Under a heavy animal welfare range the penalty can exceed the human benefit, so saving human lives looks net-harmful. Only bites once animals count, so it requires animals_somewhat; and it is a near-term human-vs-animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans), where x-risk dominates and the meat bookkeeping is moot. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 5 animals_matter_a_lot → 6 suffering_focused → 7 meat_eater_problem" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJzFWf1T20gS%2FVe6qKTOJsiW7QAJKX7gwySpkCwHbLJ3IeWMpbE9a0mjzIwQTpb87fdmJPkLG8jtVR1VVBRJ0%2FO653X3a%2FFjI%2BQDlkXmSIZ8Y2%2Bj2aT9%2FX26VEwkZCQFin2f4CJP6Cpr%2B63nlEsVhdeC55S3eu1ep7fd2%2BntUk0bmdJu3S6%2FSmDmQOssTo2QCQUjWNsjn1KmZDASLLLGWi%2Fb1K