p;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#c9b3dd;strokeColor=#4a2a78;fontColor=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="236" y="1434" width="200" height="108" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+5+8]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 5 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJzFWGtz08gS%2FStdKahrZyNbdhJIQuVDHg5QBDY3zi57L6HMWBrbs5Y0YmYUxbDht98zI8lvh%2FDpUkUh5J7u092nH6PvWyEfsCwyZzLkW0dbzSYdHx%2FTjWIiISMpUOzbBA95QrdZ22%2FtUS5VFN4JnlPe6rV7u7393gHVtJEpHdTt4dsESk60zuLUCJlQMIKuI%2FIpZUoGI8Eiq6p12KYWDZjqsZxNeqMsZomufmgTS0TMIt3TMub5iJnql10aZCZTvDzQi5kxXPVyYUa9UOhAZokRybAS358qKgVZL5JTZQeUcNNL%2BJAZccd7hWgvwrN2TnRYMCI280RoYnQ1MSM8D0TECTGa%2FaybZCxSFoZ6hxRHYEXCNUnllCnuIQAs5oAhNN6bES9i8y8Np5LA6XhFgYxTqa0PUwGcTUIOjXglCmjasCRkkUw4xchc1KAv08R07r5YqPY4v095YHDwjkUZJzlwGmY5bDhlp1wb6mcTyqwZe1DzeceOqDtSIk7pI4%2BQMU5XSv4NvcXp